00:00:41.000 --> 00:00:55.000
Coach Alex:  That's understandable. Classroom management is one of the biggest challenges for new teachers.  But it sounds like you're aware of the issue and want to find ways to improve.

00:00:56.000 --> 00:01:10.000
David:  Definitely.  I want to create a learning environment where all students feel safe and respected, but also where learning can take place without constant interruptions.

00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:25.000
Coach Alex:  Those are great goals, David.  And I can see that you already have a good rapport with your students.  They seem to respond well to you.

00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:40.000
David:  Thanks.  I try to build positive relationships with them, but sometimes I feel like I'm not assertive enough when it comes to managing behavior.

00:01:41.000 --> 00:01:55.000
Coach Alex:  That's something we can definitely work on.  It's a common challenge for teachers who want to be liked by their students.  But remember, being assertive doesn't mean being harsh or unkind.

00:01:56.000 --> 00:02:10.000
David:  That's good to hear.  I don't want to be the "mean teacher," but I also know I need to be more effective in managing disruptions.

00:02:11.000 --> 00:02:25.000
Coach Alex:  Exactly.  It's about finding that balance between being supportive and setting clear expectations.  One strategy that can help is using nonverbal cues to redirect students.

00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:40.000
David:  Like what kind of cues?

00:02:41.000 --> 00:02:55.000
Coach Alex:  Things like making eye contact with a student who's off task, giving a subtle hand gesture, or moving closer to them.  These nonverbal cues can be very effective in redirecting behavior without interrupting the flow of the lesson.

00:02:56.000 --> 00:03:10.000
David:  That makes sense.  I've tried that a few times, but I'm not always consistent with it.

00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:25.000
Coach Alex:  Consistency is key.  The more you use these nonverbal cues, the more effective they will become.  And it's important to be aware of your body language and positioning in the classroom.

00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:40.000
David:  What do you mean?

00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:55.000
Coach Alex:  Think of yourself as the conductor of an orchestra.  You need to be able to see and be seen by all of your students.  Move around the classroom, make eye contact with everyone, and use your presence to maintain order.

00:03:56.000 --> 00:04:10.000
